Now we can take the derivative of that expression:

$\begin{align}
\dfrac{d}{d\theta}y(\theta)&=\dfrac{d}{d\theta}\left[\dfrac{7\sin(\theta)}{e^\theta}\right]
\\\\
&=\dfrac{(e^{\theta})\dfrac{d}{d\theta}[7\sin(\theta)]-\dfrac{d}{d\theta}(e^{\theta})\cdot7\sin(\theta)}{(e^\theta)^2}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{(e^{\theta})7\cos(\theta)-(e^{\theta})7\sin(\theta)}{e^{2\theta}}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{7\cos(\theta)-7\sin(\theta)}{e^{\theta}}
\end{align}$

Now we can plug $\blueD{\theta=\dfrac{\pi}{2}}$ into the expression we got:

